{
  "text": "Lateral medullary syndrome (Wallenberg syndrome) is characterized by a specific constellation of symptoms. One of the most pathognomonic symptoms of Wallenberg syndrome includes pain and temperature sensory deficits of the ipsilateral face and contralateral extremities. This occurs as a result of damage to the spinal trigeminal tract and lateral spinothalamic tracts, respectively. Infarction of the vestibular nuclei may lead to vomiting, vertigo, and nystagmus, while injury to the inferior cerebellar peduncle may lead to ipsilateral ataxia. Ipsilateral pharyngeal, laryngeal, and palatal (such as dysphagia, hoarseness, and hiccups) ataxia types result from infarction of the nucleus ambiguous, the regulator of glossopharyngeal and efferent vagal reflexes. Lastly, Horner's syndrome with associated vague visual defi-cits can results from damage to the ascending sympathetic fibers. The most common vessel involved in this presentation is the vertebral artery, as seen in this case, followed by the posterior inferior cerebellar artery [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] .",
  "correct_citation": {
